200921s2017    sa ac   obc   000 0 eng d  z9780620662598q(paperback)  z062066259Xq(paperback)  a.b20136894bwww  c-  aMZAbengerdacMZAdMZA1 aSimbao, Ruth Kerkham,d1969-eauthor.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/nr00030960.10aIgshaan Adams /ctext, Ruth Simbao, Josephine Higgins, Jennifer Ball.  aRevised edition. 1aWoodstock, Cape Town :bblank projects,c2017.  a1 online resource (148 PDF pages) :billustrations.  atextbtxt2rdacontent.  acomputerbc2rdamedia.  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier.  atext filebPDF2rda.  aTitle from PDF page 3.  a"Igshaan Adams' work investigates hybrid identity, particularly in relation to race and sexuality. Adams was raised in a community racially classified in South Africa as 'coloured' under apartheid legislature. The term 'coloured' is still used in South Africa to refer to the creole community of mixed raced origins. An observant but liberal Muslim raised by Christian grandparents, Adams occupies a precarious place in his religious community because of his homosexuality. His work speaks to his experiences of racial, religious and sexual liminality, but breaks with a strong representational convention in recent South African art. Adams uses the material and formal iconographies of Islam and 'coloured' culture to develop a more equivocal, phenomenological approach towards these concerns."-- Publisher's website.  aIncludes bibliographical references.10aAdams, Igshaan,d1982-vExhibitions. 0aArt, South Africany21st centuryvExhibitions. 0aArt, Moderny20th centuryvExhibitions.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2007101136. 7aPDF.2aat0http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300266022. 0aElectronic books.1 aAdams, Igshaan,d1982-eartist.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/no2020110198.2 aBlank Projects (Gallery),eissuing body.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/no2017031000.  aCCT PDF.40uhttp://libmma.s3-website-us-east-1.amazonaws.com/1196341148.pdfzFull text PDF  